45
00:02:34.090 --> 00:02:37.400
telomeres get shorter and shorter because the DNA polymerases can't

46
00:02:38.080 --> 00:02:41.520
fully replicate the single-stranded DNA ends.

47
00:02:41.540 --> 00:02:45.420
When telomeres reach a critically short length, either cellular senescence

48
00:02:45.520 --> 00:02:47.180
or apoptosis are triggered and

49
00:02:48.320 --> 00:02:51.620
that's sort of that. But in some settings, cells can upregulate

50
00:02:51.660 --> 00:02:55.300
p53, Rb, other pathways, and continue to

51
00:02:55.380 --> 00:02:58.060
divide despite having critically short telomeres.

52
00:02:58.720 --> 00:03:02.100
There's also mechanisms where cells can increase activity of

53
00:03:02.140 --> 00:03:05.740
telomerase, which extends telomeric ends, or use an

54
00:03:05.800 --> 00:03:09.500
alternate lengthening of telomere measurement, a telomere-length lengthening,

55
00:03:10.080 --> 00:03:10.290
and

56
00:03:11.100 --> 00:03:14.410
continue to lengthen their telomeres, continue to divide,

57
00:03:14.470 --> 00:03:18.390
accumulate somatic mutations, and send those cells down that

58
00:03:18.400 --> 00:03:22.260
carcinogenic pathways. So, as a little bit more

59
00:03:22.280 --> 00:03:26.120
background, when we think about germline telomere length, so

60
00:03:26.200 --> 00:03:29.660
what I just talked about was in cancer cells.

61
00:03:29.740 --> 00:03:32.020
Now we're talking about in the germline setting.

62
00:03:32.560 --> 00:03:36.220
There are lots of epidemiology studies that have

63
00:03:36.260 --> 00:03:40.060
looked at telomere length, whether it's in blood, buccal cells, a

64
00:03:40.100 --> 00:03:43.920
few others, as well as single nucleotide polymorphisms or

65
00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:47.920
common variants in association with telomere length that have found

66
00:03:48.140 --> 00:03:51.450
a key role of telomeres in cancer etiology and

67
00:03:51.480 --> 00:03:53.520
cardiovascular disease etiology.

68
00:03:54.200 --> 00:03:58.020
And those are all people in the general population who, if you measure

69
00:03:58.060 --> 00:04:01.510
their telomeres, they're going to be somewhere between that first and

70
00:04:01.720 --> 00:04:03.800
99th percentile for telomere length.

71
00:04:04.220 --> 00:04:08.020
And these are all common variants, more than 1% minor allele

72
00:04:08.040 --> 00:04:08.549
frequency.

73
00:04:09.740 --> 00:04:13.500
At the other end of the spectrum, which is actually something I'm not going to talk

