transplant data. For obvious reasons, we didn't have enough to look at,

245
00:14:36.260 --> 00:14:37.580
say, donor-derived leukemia.

246
00:14:38.560 --> 00:14:42.180
But when we look, the risk of AML is again around 50-fold

247
00:14:42.260 --> 00:14:46.000
higher than the general population. MDS, around 500.

248
00:14:46.100 --> 00:14:49.320
Again, with some caveats that these are relatively small numbers.

249
00:14:50.060 --> 00:14:53.680
But again, you see some subtle differences in the

250
00:14:54.540 --> 00:14:58.310
dominant versus recessive or the heterozygote versus the biallelic patients,

251
00:14:58.400 --> 00:15:02.180
but still very high risks of hematopoietic

252
00:15:02.240 --> 00:15:03.600
cancers in this population.

253
00:15:05.280 --> 00:15:07.660
So what's happening in the blood of these patients?

254
00:15:08.120 --> 00:15:11.840
So one of the things that we and others have looked at is somatic rescue.

255
00:15:12.360 --> 00:15:16.120
So this is a really nice review if anyone's interested in learning more,

256
00:15:16.300 --> 00:15:16.580
where

257
00:15:17.480 --> 00:15:21.330
what we see in patients with TBDs is both direct and

258
00:15:21.380 --> 00:15:25.090
indirect hematopoietic rescue, where by direct I mean

259
00:15:25.100 --> 00:15:28.520
basically a back mutation of the disease-causing gene.

260
00:15:29.100 --> 00:15:32.480
And indirect, we have compensatory mutations that help

261
00:15:32.540 --> 00:15:36.280
improve the hematopoietic phenotype, for example, with a TERT

262
00:15:36.300 --> 00:15:37.340
promoter mutation.

263
00:15:38.900 --> 00:15:42.600
In collaboration with the National Heart, Lung, and Blood

264
00:15:42.680 --> 00:15:46.420
Institute cohort and a cohort in Sao Paulo, Brazil,

265
00:15:47.060 --> 00:15:50.940
we showed that the acquisition of somatic mutations in

266
00:15:50.980 --> 00:15:54.120
our patients with TBDs was associated with the

267
00:15:54.160 --> 00:15:58.110
clinical outcomes. So patients who

268
00:15:58.110 --> 00:16:01.900
had clonal hematopoiesis that was not associated with cancer

269
00:16:02.020 --> 00:16:05.540
had mutations in POT1, in the TERT promoter, and in

270
00:16:05.620 --> 00:16:09.400
PPM1D. And then those that were associated with the development of

271
00:16:09.440 --> 00:16:13.380
cancer were, as you might expect, loss of P53,

272
00:16:13.580 --> 00:16:17.540
MDM4 overexpression, U2AF1 mutations.

273
00:16:18.500 --> 00:16:20.800
And just to sort of summarize that part of

274
00:16:20.860 --> 00:16:24.350
the somatic mutation piece is

275
00:16:24.400 --> 00:16:28.179
that telomere dysfunction appears to be a strong selective

276
00:16:28.200 --> 00:16:30.040
pressure for clonal hematopoiesis.

277
00:16:30.660 --> 00:16:34.600
It appears to be a poor prognostic marker, again though, depending on

278
00:16:34.640 --> 00:16:38.360
which mutation you have. And that we're really working

279
00:16:38.400 --> 00:16:42.150
hard as a field to identify the regulatory pathways that's

280
00:16:42.160 --> 00:16:46.020
driving this clonal transformation in TBDs so that we can identify

281
00:16:46.060 --> 00:16:48.820
patients who are at risk of cancer development.

282
00:16:48.890 --> 00:16:50.700
And this is key because

283
00:16:51.520 --> 00:16:53.500
a lot of these patients have bone marrow failure.

284
00:16:54.460 --> 00:16:56.940
Just because they have bone marrow failure doesn't always mean they need a

285
00:16:57.000 --> 00:16:57.700
transplant.

286
00:16:58.680 --> 00:17:02.380
But you want to be able to monitor them and intervene early if it looks

287
00:17:02.420 --> 00:17:06.381
like their counts are going down and/or they're acquiring

288
00:17:06.421 --> 00:17:09.940
one of these somatic mutations, so then you can transplant them earlier.

289
00:17:10.780 --> 00:17:14.590
And with a clinical care consortium, we are combining

290
00:17:14.620 --> 00:17:17.911
retrospective data across around 600 or

291
00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:21.860
700 patients around the world, and also working towards a

292
00:17:21.901 --> 00:17:25.840
prospective study to get more information on

293
00:17:25.921 --> 00:17:29.800
how to identify and better monitor the

294
00:17:29.880 --> 00:17:32.170
acquisition of somatic mutations in these patients.

295
00:17:34.350 --> 00:17:38.060
So I mentioned very briefly, a lot of our patients who

296
00:17:38.080 --> 00:17:41.520
present in childhood have immunodeficiency, and in fact some of our

297
00:17:41.900 --> 00:17:45.620
TINF2, our biallelic RTEL1 patients, our biallelic

298
00:17:45.700 --> 00:17:49.660
TERT patients, actually can present in infancy or as toddlers

299
00:17:49.720 --> 00:17:53.040
with very difficult to diagnose immunodeficiencies.

300
00:17:53.820 --> 00:17:56.940
So there's been a couple papers just in the last year or so

301
00:17:57.720 --> 00:18:01.700
that have started to really try to define the immune profile of telomere biology

302
00:18:01.760 --> 00:18:05.640
disorders. And what we're finding is that there is reduced thymic

303
00:18:05.760 --> 00:18:09.660
output, abnormal maturation of

304
00:18:09.700 --> 00:18:12.780
lymphocytes, exhaustion of T lymphocytes,

305
00:18:13.200 --> 00:18:17.020
unconventional T cells, pro-inflammatory profiles.

306
00:18:17.660 --> 00:18:21.380
There's a lymphopenia.That is associated with the

307
00:18:21.420 --> 00:18:25.250
immunodeficiency. And I didn't have time to put it here,

308
00:18:25.360 --> 00:18:27.980
so these studies had really focused on T cells.

309
00:18:28.020 --> 00:18:31.710
We have some really interesting data that we're kind of sorting through,

310
00:18:31.820 --> 00:18:34.120
suggesting there's also a B cell defect.

311
00:18:36.600 --> 00:18:40.080
So this is a model that I recently developed of

312
00:18:40.150 --> 00:18:44.080
thinking of carcinogenesis in the telomere biology disorders.

313
00:18:44.800 --> 00:18:48.500
And again, in these TBDs, we have really two

314
00:18:48.540 --> 00:18:52.360
things going on. One is we have some patients who have germline

315
00:18:52.600 --> 00:18:56.480
variants that prevent telomerase from doing its job, so

316
00:18:56.520 --> 00:18:58.900
they're preventing telomere elongation.

317
00:18:58.920 --> 00:19:02.880
And this happens in utero, so these are patients who are born

318
00:19:03.180 --> 00:19:05.500
with really, really short telomeres. Okay?

319
00:19:05.620 --> 00:19:09.600
It's not an accelerated shortening, it's just their set point is way lower

320
00:19:09.620 --> 00:19:13.240
than it should be. So some patients, telomerase can't do its

321
00:19:13.300 --> 00:19:16.900
job. Other patients, like our shelterin complex mutations,

322
00:19:16.980 --> 00:19:20.520
TENF2 is one I've mentioned a lot, it's the most common shelterin

323
00:19:20.560 --> 00:19:23.719
mutation, actually can't protect their telomeres.

324
00:19:24.170 --> 00:19:27.990
So telomerase might be there trying to do its job, but there's no protection at

325
00:19:28.020 --> 00:19:31.360
those chromosome ends. So they have these short

326
00:19:31.500 --> 00:19:35.260
and/or unstable telomeres that can lead to an

327
00:19:35.280 --> 00:19:39.120
accumulation of mutations, genomic instability, and then we're just

328
00:19:39.160 --> 00:19:42.940
getting at some of the data that's suggesting that there's suboptimal immune

329
00:19:43.060 --> 00:19:46.500
surveillance, at least looking at how we're

330
00:19:46.540 --> 00:19:49.540
characterizing the immune deficiency in these patients.

331
00:19:49.620 --> 00:19:53.280
Ongoing oxidative stress, because it's this sort of vicious cycle of

332
00:19:53.420 --> 00:19:56.160
abnormal DNA repair, oxidative

333
00:19:56.540 --> 00:19:58.860
phosphorylation, getting active and

334
00:19:59.660 --> 00:20:03.540
producing reactive oxygen species, et cetera, and then we're

335
00:20:03.580 --> 00:20:07.480
developing cancer. There's a lot of pieces there that we either don't know

336
00:20:07.520 --> 00:20:11.390
or I haven't had a chance to describe in detail, but I kind of wanted to put this

337
00:20:11.420 --> 00:20:13.520
concept out there.

338
00:20:14.600 --> 00:20:18.440
So about treating cancers, what do we do with these patients who do

339
00:20:18.540 --> 00:20:22.400
develop cancers? The short answer is we don't really know,

340
00:20:23.080 --> 00:20:26.420
unfortunately. There's no clinical trial data.

341
00:20:26.500 --> 00:20:30.280
I recently did a literature review where I found 25

342
00:20:30.380 --> 00:20:33.960
cases in the literature that had at least some kind of

343
00:20:34.020 --> 00:20:37.850
information about cancer treatment, and it was

344
00:20:37.900 --> 00:20:41.860
all very dismal in that doses were adjusted, outcomes were

345
00:20:41.920 --> 00:20:42.480
still poor,

346
00:20:43.500 --> 00:20:44.800
side effects were really bad.

347
00:20:46.700 --> 00:20:50.390
And when we looked just in our cohort, which is very limited, and the

348
00:20:51.260 --> 00:20:54.100
timer's not working correctly, so I'm guessing.

349
00:20:55.820 --> 00:20:56.160
Sorry.

350
00:20:57.000 --> 00:21:00.020
I looked at our cohort data. Now this is very much a

351
00:21:00.320 --> 00:21:01.920
descriptive snapshot,

352
00:21:02.920 --> 00:21:06.560
and it's a study that we're just wanting to kind of get

353
00:21:06.600 --> 00:21:10.480
together. But when we looked at six patients who had AML in our cohort,

354
00:21:10.920 --> 00:21:13.600
and unfortunately, all of them died due to disease.

355
00:21:14.460 --> 00:21:15.469
And they were really

356
00:21:16.480 --> 00:21:20.070
not good deaths, very toxic, very complicated

357
00:21:20.080 --> 00:21:23.960
patients. Two patients with non-Hodgkin lymphoma died within a

358
00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:25.060
year of diagnosis.

359
00:21:26.060 --> 00:21:29.420
One outcome was unknown. We've had some patients treated with

360
00:21:29.460 --> 00:21:33.420
rituximab for PTLD after transplant who have done okay, but we

361
00:21:33.460 --> 00:21:35.660
don't have really complete outcome data.

362
00:21:36.980 --> 00:21:40.809
When I looked specifically in our cohort at head and neck squamous cell cancers,

363
00:21:41.300 --> 00:21:44.840
you can see 21 cancers in only 11 patients.

364
00:21:45.420 --> 00:21:49.350
One patient who had a TERT heterozygous mutation had

365
00:21:49.420 --> 00:21:53.380
11 resections, and unfortunately, she passed away from head

366
00:21:53.400 --> 00:21:55.160
and neck cancer just two years ago.

367
00:21:55.960 --> 00:21:57.820
Three patients with one resection each.

368
00:21:58.020 --> 00:22:01.900
We had patients with seven invasive cancers, and unfortunately for all

369
00:22:01.960 --> 00:22:05.420
of these seven patients, one is unknown, and

370
00:22:05.500 --> 00:22:08.260
unfortunately, the outcomes were very poor for the other six.

371
00:22:09.480 --> 00:22:13.120
So what can we do right now? I think I'm pointing out all kinds of

372
00:22:13.160 --> 00:22:17.140
questions in cancer in the TBDs. And what we have right

373
00:22:17.180 --> 00:22:21.140
now is based on sort of expert opinion across the field,

374
00:22:22.360 --> 00:22:26.060
built in our clinical care guidelines, which is screening, early

375
00:22:26.120 --> 00:22:28.980
detection, trying to get our patients into the

376
00:22:29.000 --> 00:22:32.540
otolaryngologist who actually is willing to see a

377
00:22:32.640 --> 00:22:36.520
kid for a cancer screening, okay? That's a challenge for

378
00:22:36.540 --> 00:22:37.460
our families, too.

379
00:22:39.480 --> 00:22:42.840
Educating their dentists, their ENTs, following their

380
00:22:43.400 --> 00:22:46.740
physical exams, doing all those good things that we're supposed to

381
00:22:46.780 --> 00:22:50.480
be doing or not doing in preventing cancer in the general

382
00:22:50.520 --> 00:22:53.100
population. So avoiding sun, avoiding smoking,

383
00:22:55.420 --> 00:22:58.040
all of HPV vaccines as well.

384
00:22:59.620 --> 00:23:03.460
And I will end there and just say that very recently,

385
00:23:03.860 --> 00:23:07.640
Dr. Richa Sharma, who's a new investigator at the Cleveland Clinic,

386
00:23:07.700 --> 00:23:11.520
has initiated a national DNA repair and telomere biology disorder

387
00:23:11.620 --> 00:23:14.400
tumor board. It's separate from the Fanconi anemia

388
00:23:15.600 --> 00:23:17.090
tumor board, and

389
00:23:17.980 --> 00:23:21.800
we've had two meetings so far. They've been great, and if you have

390
00:23:21.860 --> 00:23:24.740
cases you want to share, please send them to us.

